data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you inspect the exception and pinpoints exactly which line should throw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify details
}
```

**Why:**
- `[ExpectedException]` is obsolete — it can't distinguish *which* line threw
- `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` matches the exact type (use `Assert.Throws<T>` if derived types should also pass)
- You get the exception instance back, so you can assert on `Message`, `ParamName`, etc.
